<body>
<sec id="section1-1527002512438616">
<title>Introduction</title>
<p>It is now several years since a series of articles were published claiming to show that the invariance principle does not hold for the conventional model of a sports league when properly specified as a game (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr5-1527002512438616">Szymanski, 2003</xref>, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1527002512438616">2004</xref>; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr7-1527002512438616">Szymanski &amp; Kesenne, 2004</xref>). These articles spawned a small rebuttal literature asserting that their claims were either wholly or partially false, referred to in a recent note in this journal by <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1527002512438616">Fort and Winfree (2012</xref>, henceforth FW). FW argue that the “SK model [by which they mean the model employed in the three articles mentioned above] does not fully take into account additional, crucial difference between leagues with open talent market and leagues with closed talent markets,” that “some research subsequent to the SK critique is also confused on the open and closed market distinction,” and that “confusion continues to reign on this issue.” They suggest “all of this confusion is resolved by adding one more modeling dimension to capture both the elasticity of talent supply.” Having done so, they concede that conventional “model need not exhibit the invariance principle” but claim that using a specific assumption “the invariance principle holds for the closed market.”</p>
<p>This comment does three things as follows:<list list-type="order">
<list-item>
<p>Sets out briefly the modeling issue.</p>
</list-item>
<list-item>
<p>Claims that <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr7-1527002512438616">Szymanski and Kesenne (2004)</xref> and <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1527002512438616">Szymanski (2004)</xref> explicitly dealt with the questions raised by FW.</p>
</list-item>
<list-item>
<p>Shows that both for the Tullock functional form typically adopted in the literature, and for a very wide class of contest success functions, the invariance principle cannot hold. The one contest success for which it could hold makes no sense in the professional team sports context.</p>
</list-item>
</list>
</p>
</sec>
<sec id="section2-1527002512438616">
<title>The Modeling Issue</title>
<p>It is important to be clear what is meant by the “conventional model” and “properly specified.” The conventional model involves two profit maximizing teams which generate revenue from success in a contest through investment in playing talent. Success is measured by win percentage (which in a two team league must add up to 1).<list list-type="simple">
<list-item>
<p>Claim 1: Teams clearly cannot choose win percentage directly (unless the league is fixed), but if they can choose talent, they can indirectly influence win percentage.</p>
</list-item>
<list-item>
<p>Claim 2: Teams also cannot choose talent directly if the supply of talent is fixed and fully employed, since the quantity allocated to Team 1 will also depend on the quantity allocated to Team 2 (if talent is not fully employed, then it would be possible to choose a quantity independently of the other team).</p>
</list-item>
</list>The logical way to approach the modeling in these circumstances is to allow teams to compete via the choice of a variable which is unconstrained by the choices of the other team, and then allow these choices to feed through to win percentage via a set of identities. Most simply, each team independently allocates a budget (e.g., in U.S. dollars) to investment in talent, which then determines the share of talent that each team is able to acquire and in turn determines the win percentage of each team. In fact, even if the supply of talent were perfectly elastic (the open league case), this is still the logical (and most realistic) way to characterize the problem.</p>
<p>Writing this down formally, we can say that <italic>w</italic>
<sub>1</sub> = <italic>w</italic>
<sub>1</sub> (<italic>t</italic>
<sub>1</sub> (<italic>z</italic>
