</sec>
<sec id="section3-1527002512438616">
<title>Is This News?</title>
<p>FW admit “the only other work that carefully distinguishes between talent, itself, and talent investment” (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1527002512438616">Szymanski, 2004</xref>, footnote 8, p. 125). That footnote also states “It should be obvious that the Nash equilibrium of the game in which Z is the choice variable is exactly equivalent to the Nash equilibrium of game described in the rest of this article in which t is the choice variable.” The only difference between the model in which talent is chosen and investment is chosen is the substitution of the letter “<italic>Z</italic>” for the letter “<italic>t</italic>”—which obviously cannot affect the result.</p>
<p>FW seem to have missed the section of <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr7-1527002512438616">Szymanski and Kesenne (2004)</xref>, which also addresses this issue. Appendix 2 of the abovesaid article (pp. 176–177) derives the necessary equations for modeling the case where team choose investment levels rather than talent (using instead the letter <italic>I</italic> rather than <italic>Z</italic>). If there is confusion, as FW suggest, then given that the issue is explicitly modeled in both <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1527002512438616">Szymanski (2004)</xref> and <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr7-1527002512438616">Szymanski and Kesenne (2004)</xref>, the problem may be that critics did not read these articles carefully enough.</p>
</sec>
