</mml:math>
</inline-formula> This kind of function was first explored in the contest literature by <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr3-1527002512438616">Hirshleifer (1989)</xref>, which he dubbed the “difference model” as opposed to the “ratio model,” since the exponential function depends on the difference rather than the ratio of resources deployed. However, the difference model is not homogeneous of degree zero, which in the context of a sports league where teams spend money buying talent makes no sense. It would imply, for example, that the Yankees would win more games against their rivals if team budgets were expressed in Chinese Yuan rather than in U.S. dollars (since then the difference would be larger).</p>
<p>Despite repeated attempts to salvage the invariance principle, it still seems impossible to specify a reasonable version of the standard model in which it can survive. As <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr8-1527002512438616">Tremblay (2009)</xref> observes, a different modeling approach, for example, introducing a dynamic framework, might be more fruitful. In my view, the most significant contribution to this literature since 2004 is <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr4-1527002512438616">Madden (2010)</xref>, who incorporates the market power of the teams in the labor market into the model and shows that revenue sharing can weaken or improve competitive balance, with the invariance principle representing a boundary between two regimes.</p>
